# Tailwind CSS v4 Theme Variables Guide

## Core Concept

Theme variables are CSS variables defined with the `@theme` directive that instruct Tailwind to generate corresponding utility classes. As the documentation states: **"Theme variables are special CSS variables defined using the `@theme` directive that influence which utility classes exist in your project."**

## Key Differences: @theme vs :root

The `@theme` directive serves a dual purposeâ€”it both creates CSS variables AND generates utilities. Regular `:root` variables are purely stylistic. **"Since they do more than regular CSS variables, Tailwind uses special syntax so that defining theme variables is always explicit."**

## Theme Variable Namespaces

Variables organize by namespace, each mapping to utility classes:

| Namespace | Generated Utilities |
|-----------|-------------------|
| `--color-*` | `bg-`, `text-`, `fill-`, etc. |
| `--font-*` | `font-sans`, `font-serif` |
| `--spacing-*` | `px-`, `py-`, `max-h-`, sizing |
| `--radius-*` | `rounded-sm`, `rounded-lg` |
| `--shadow-*` | `shadow-md`, `shadow-lg` |
| `--breakpoint-*` | Responsive variants (`sm:*`, `md:*`) |

## Customization Patterns

**Extending the default theme:**
```css
@import "tailwindcss";
@theme {
  --font-poppins: Poppins, sans-serif;
}
```

**Overriding defaults:**
```css
@theme {
  --breakpoint-sm: 30rem;  /* Changes sm: breakpoint */
}
```

**Complete replacement** (reset namespace):
```css
@theme {
  --color-*: initial;  /* Remove all default colors */
  --color-primary: #3f3cbb;
}
```

## Advanced Techniques

**Referencing other variables** requires the `inline` option to prevent CSS variable resolution issues:
```css
@theme inline {
  --font-sans: var(--font-inter);
}
```

**Animation keyframes** within `@theme`:
```css
@theme {
  --animate-fade: fade 0.3s ease-out;
  @keyframes fade { /* defined here */ }
}
```

**Sharing across projects** via separate CSS files enables design token consistency across monorepos or npm packages.

## Runtime Access

All theme variables become standard CSS variables available to custom CSS and JavaScript:
```javascript
getComputedStyle(document.documentElement)
  .getPropertyValue("--shadow-xl");
```

This enables design token consistency across styling approaches and frameworks.

